SIMPLE: procurator
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Procurator
<hw>Proc"u*ra`tor</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.: cf. F.
<ets>procurateur</ets>. See <er>Procure</er>, and cf. <er>Proctor</er>.
]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who manages another's affairs,
either generally or in a special matter; an agent; a proctor.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer. Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A governor of a province
under the emperors; also, one who had charge of the imperial revenues in
a province; <as>as, the <ex>procurator</ex> of Judea</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Procurator fiscal</b></col> <fld>(Scots Law)</fld>,
<cd>public prosecutor, or district attorney.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Procuratorial</ent>⟦br⟧
